steps.reasoning: The user is looking for high-protein, low-carb options under $3 each. The dietary_filter tool can help find items that match these dietary preferences. I'll use "low_carb" as the restriction parameter since it best matches the user's request for low-carb options. After getting these results, I can filter them further for high-protein items under $3.

data.esql:
FROM grocery_items
| LOOKUP JOIN nutrition_facts ON item_id
| LOOKUP JOIN store_inventory ON item_id
| WHERE stock_status != "out_of_stock"
| EVAL meets_restriction = CASE(
    "low_carb" == "vegan", vegan == true,
    "low_carb" == "gluten_free", gluten_free == true,
    "low_carb" == "organic", organic == true,
    "low_carb" == "low_carb", total_carbs < 10,
    "low_carb" == "high_protein", protein > 15,
    true
  )
| WHERE meets_restriction == true
| EVAL final_price = CASE(on_sale, sale_price, current_price)
| SORT final_price ASC
| LIMIT 20

steps.reasoning: Now I need to find high-protein options to complement the low-carb items I found. The user specifically asked for high-protein, low-carb options under $3 each. The search_grocery_items tool will help me find items that are high in protein, which I can then filter to match the other criteria (low-carb and under $3).

data.esql:
FROM grocery_items
| WHERE name: "high protein" OR category: "high protein" OR description: "high protein"
| LOOKUP JOIN store_inventory ON item_id
| WHERE stock_status != "out_of_stock"
| EVAL final_price = CASE(on_sale, sale_price, current_price)
| STATS avg_price = AVG(final_price), 
        min_price = MIN(final_price),
        max_price = MAX(final_price),
        stores_available = COUNT_DISTINCT(store_id)
  BY item_id, name, brand, category, unit_size, organic, gluten_free, vegan
| WHERE stores_available > 0
| SORT avg_price ASC
| LIMIT 20
